    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-2382449">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-2382449">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2382449)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2382449">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kalinin" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2203795); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2203795&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183131" alt="Kalinin" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2203795)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/kalinin" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2203795); return false;" >Kalinin</a></span> <span class="odate time_1443380521 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">27 Sep 2015 19:02</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2382449">
									

<p>Using <a href="/scp-012">SCP-012</a> as the starting point for a major project seems problematic to me. That's part of a more general issue I have when people expend lots of energy and effort trying to invest thin or boring starting concepts with meaning and interest. Frequently, you end up with something that's better-written than the original, but ultimately it's still uninteresting.</p>
<p>This is apparently the start of something ongoing, so time will tell if this work as a whole falls into that trap. This particular installment isn't really pointing the way to much beyond the boundaries of the original article (an article that's not very good, FWIW). Really, this amounts to an extremely detailed recovery log and testing log interspersed with some commentary. The only real new information is the fact that it's close to being finished, but that's still within the boundaries of the original concept. It's not really making me reconsider the original premise or making it feel much different to me.</p>
<p>The writing itself is okay, though the language in the journal entries is a little florid. I suppose that can be chalked up to the fact that this guy has at least a little antiquarian in him, but it reads very much like a standard-issue Lovecraftian &quot;guy what goes crazy&quot; narrative. That might not have been a problem in and of itself, but the narrative arc of the journals has already been described in the original article and I'm expecting it, and there it is being dutifully carried out.</p>
<p>I may reevaluate this upon subsequent works, but right now, I'm not seeing why 012 is worth the effort, which I think should be one of the main points of this project you're working on.</p>

							</div>

								
					
