    <div class="post-container" id="fpc-2383436">
                      
		<div class="post" id="post-2383436">
		<div class="long">
			<div class="head">
									<div class="options">
						<a href="javascript:;" onclick="togglePostFold(event,2383436)" class="btn btn-default btn-small btn-sm">Fold</a>
					</div>
								<div class="title" id="post-title-2383436">
																		
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/psul" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2156983); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=2156983&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610183131" alt="psul" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=2156983)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/psul" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(2156983); return false;" >psul</a></span> <span class="odate time_1443513662 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">29 Sep 2015 08:01</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2383436">
									

<p>It's interesting to see the number of people who want this idea to do well, but are nervous about the difficulty of execution. I would also put myself in that category, despite being quite keen to write for the canon if inspiration strikes.</p>
<p>I was pleased with the result here overall. The middle section in particular is evocative and engaging, and doesn't tip its hand too early in relation to insanity. I also like that it provides backstory without completely settling matters - there's at least one more story to tell.</p>
<p>I feel like the opening section has slightly too many &quot;he&quot;s and &quot;she&quot;s, as well as &quot;he asks&quot;, &quot;he says&quot; - it feels a bit static.</p>
<p>8-13 November entries are the ones I particularly like - great photos and I'm not too maxed out on purple to find the prose cliche.</p>
<p>In 12 November, I think &quot;our late composer's&quot; is too early - he would just be a &quot;late musician&quot; as the contents of the papers are unknown.</p>
<p>For 14 November, presumably the reference to 7/12 meter (which does not compute in standard Western musical notation) is deliberate. I didn't quite understand the interaction here - Spitzer mutters something about containment, but Anderson is later revealed as the Foundation agent. Also &quot;All the best&quot; made no sense to me.</p>
<p>As 15 November is a &quot;cheat&quot; diary where the writer appears to write in the middle of acting, I suggest that it not have a picture. I think you can use this picture (which is great) for 13 November (which is not as strong). &quot;He has locked the door&quot;- I couldn't work out whether that was Spitzer or Anderson. Finally, I would lose the paragraph about karate - that felt odd, partly because I thought Spitzer was handcuffed to the bed, and partly because Asian martial art names don't fit the purple prose. Presumably KM can simply steal the key and hide it for later.</p>
<p>In 16 November, I would be tempted to make the red colour slightly darker.</p>

							</div>

								
					
